# 1. Introduction

Two Pointers is one of the most important optimization techniques in DSA.

It uses two indices (pointers) to traverse a data structure efficiently.

Instead of:

```java
for(i)
   for(j)
```

(O(N²))

We use:

```java
left++;
right--;
```

or

```java
slow++;
fast++;
```

to achieve:

```text
O(N)
```

in many problems.

---

# 2. What is Two Pointers?

Two Pointers means using two variables pointing to different positions and moving them according to certain conditions.

Example:

```java
int left = 0;
int right = arr.length - 1;
```

```text
[1,2,3,4,5]

 L       R
```

Pointers move based on problem requirements.

---

# 3. Why Two Pointers?

Without Two Pointers:

```java
O(N²)
```

With Two Pointers:

```java
O(N)
```

Huge optimization.

Example:

Find pair with sum = target.

Brute Force:

```java
for(i)
   for(j)
```

Time:

```text
O(N²)
```

Two Pointers:

```java
left = 0
right = n-1
```

Time:

```text
O(N)
```

